IMPORTANT NOTES FOR CLAUDE CODE\
\
1. Do not use standard Servo.h \'97 use PWMServo.h for Teensy. The library has 
\f1\fs26 \cb4 servo.writeMicroseconds()
\f0\fs28 \cb3  not 
\f1\fs26 \cb4 servo.write()
\f0\fs28 \cb3  for pulse-width control.\
2. IntervalTimer callback must be minimal \'97 only set 
\f1\fs26 \cb4 control_flag = true
\f0\fs28 \cb3 . Never do I2C reads or SD writes inside the ISR. All real work in loop().\
3. Servo pins are intentionally blank \'97 left as -1 with TODO comments. The user will fill these in before flashing. Do not hardcode them.\
4. Axis mapping comment \'97 add a clear comment in mpu_read() that the user must verify gyro_x\uc0\u8594 pitch, gyro_y\u8594 yaw mapping matches their physical IMU mounting orientation. A 90\'b0 rotation error is easy to introduce.\
5. Gimbal sign convention \'97 add comment: positive pitch error \uc0\u8594  positive gimbal command \u8594  motor tilts to push nose back toward vertical. If rocket overcorrects, flip the sign in the PID call: 
\f1\fs26 \cb4 pid_pitch.update(-est_pitch, dt)
\f0\fs28 \cb3  stays negative (corrective), but user should verify direction on bench before live fire.\
6. CSV column format is fixed \'97 the Python post-processing script expects exactly the header defined above. Do not change column names or order.\
7. SG90 pulse calibration \'97 note in comments that SG90 pulse range (500\'962500 \'b5s) may need calibration per-servo. Add 
\f1\fs26 \cb4 SERVO_MIN_US
\f0\fs28 \cb3  and 
\f1\fs26 \cb4 SERVO_MAX_US
\f0\fs28 \cb3  as user-adjustable constants.\
8. Paper note on servo model \'97 the paper's control effort section refers to MG90S servos but the firmware is written for SG90s. The user should verify which servo they are actually using and adjust pulse ranges accordingly. Add this as a comment in the servo section.\
